Neural Network with http://scikit-learn.org/¶

"A feedforward neural network is an artificial neural network wherein connections between the nodes do not form a cycle. As such, it is different from recurrent neural networks.

The feedforward neural network was the first and simplest type of artificial neural network devised. In this network, the information moves in only one direction, forward, from the input nodes, through the hidden nodes (if any) and to the output nodes. There are no cycles or loops in the network." wikipedia.org

Multi-layer Perceptron (MLP) is a supervised learning algorithm that learns a function by training on a dataset. It can learn a non-linear function approximator for either classification or regression. It is different from logistic regression, in that between the input and the output layer, there can be one or more non-linear layers, called hidden layers. scikit-learn.org

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from sklearn import datasets
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn import preprocessing

plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8.0, 6.0)

# Krok 1 - załadowanie danych
boston_market_data = datasets.load_boston()

# Krok 2 - podział danych na testujące i uczące 
boston_train_data, boston_test_data, \
boston_train_target, boston_test_target = \
train_test_split(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(boston_market_data['data']),\
                 boston_market_data['target'], test_size=0.1, random_state=1)

print("boston_train_data.shape", boston_train_data.shape)
print("boston_test_data.shape", boston_test_data.shape)

# Krok 3 - tworzenie modelu regresji liniowej 
linear_regression = LinearRegression()

# Krok 4 - uczenie modelu
linear_regression.fit(boston_train_data, boston_train_target)

# Krok 5 - wyświetlenie błędu średnio kwadratowego
print("Mean squared error of a learned linear model: %.2f" % 
      mean_squared_error(boston_test_target, linear_regression.predict(boston_test_data)))

boston_train_data.shape (455, 13)
boston_test_data.shape (51, 13)
Mean squared error of a learned linear model: 20.54

from sklearn.neural_network import MLPRegressor

# Krok 1 - tworzenie modelu
neural_network = MLPRegressor(hidden_layer_sizes=(30,20,10,), activation='logistic', solver="sgd", \
                              batch_size=20, shuffle=True, momentum=0.95, alpha=1e-5, verbose=False, \
                              max_iter=500, tol=1e-7, random_state=1)

# Krok 2 - uczenie modelu
neural_network.fit(boston_train_data, boston_train_target)

# Krok 3 - obliczenie MSE
print("Mean squared error of a learned neural network model: %.2f" % 
      mean_squared_error(boston_test_target, neural_network.predict(boston_test_data)))

Mean squared error of a learned neural network model: 5.91

# Porównywanie błędu R2 dwóch modeli, można zauważyć, że model sieci neuronowej jest o wiele lepszy

print('Variance score for neural network model: %.2f' % r2_score(boston_test_target, neural_network.predict(boston_test_data)))

Finding metaparameters for neural network using GridSearch()

In [17]:
# Znajdowanie metaparametrów dla sieci neuronowej za pomocą GridSearch ()
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

parameters = {'solver': ['adam', 'sgd'], 'max_iter': [500], \
              'hidden_layer_sizes':[(100,), (30,20,10,)], \
              'random_state':np.arange(0,2), 'tol':[1e-7], 'batch_size':[20,60], 'shuffle':[True, False],\
              'momentum':[0.95,0.85], 'activation': ['logistic','relu'], 'alpha':[1e-5,1e-6]}

# Krok 1 - utwórz gridsearcha
grid_search = GridSearchCV(MLPRegressor(), parameters, n_jobs=-1, verbose=1, cv=4)

# Krok 2 - załaduj i naucz model
grid_search.fit(boston_train_data, boston_train_target)
        
# Krok 3 - wynik
print(grid_search.score(boston_test_data, boston_test_target))

# Krok 4 - podaj
';lnajlepsze parametry
print(grid_search.best_params_)

# Import danych
from keras.datasets import fashion_mnist

# Metryki poprawności
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Regresja logistyczna
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Seaborn is a library for making statistical graphics in Python
import seaborn as sns

# Podział na trenujące i testujące
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = fashion_mnist.load_data()

# Krok 1 - utworzenie zbioru trenującego
images_train =  []
for image_train in x_train:
    images_train.append(image_train.flatten())

# Krok 2 - utworzenie zbioru testującego
images_test = []
for image_test in x_test:
    images_test.append(image_test.flatten())

# Krok 3 - utworzenie tablic
images_train = np.array(images_train)
images_test = np.array(images_test)

# Krok 4 - utworzenie modelu regresji logistycznej
linear_model = LogisticRegression(verbose=1, max_iter=10, multi_class="multinomial", solver="sag")

# Krok 5 - uczenie modelu
linear_model.fit(images_train, y_train)

# Krok 6 - utworzenie macierzy konfuzji
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, linear_model.predict(images_test))

# Wizualizacja wyników
print("Confusion_matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix)

from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier

# Import danych
from keras.datasets import fashion_mnist

# Metryki poprawności
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Regresja logistyczna
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Seaborn is a library for making statistical graphics in Python
import seaborn as sns

# Podział na trenujące i testujące
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = fashion_mnist.load_data()

# Krok 1 - utworzenie zbioru trenującego
images_train =  []
for image_train in x_train:
    images_train.append(image_train.flatten())

# Krok 2 - utworzenie zbioru testującego
images_test = []
for image_test in x_test:
    images_test.append(image_test.flatten())

# Krok 3 - utworzenie tablic
images_train = np.array(images_train)
images_test = np.array(images_test)

# Utworzenie sieci neuronowej
neural_network = MLPClassifier(hidden_layer_sizes=(100,50,25),activation ='relu', random_state=1)

# Standaryzacja i nauka modelu
neural_network.fit(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(images_train), y_train)

# Utworzenie macierzy konfuzji
conf_matrix_neural_network = confusion_matrix(y_test, \
                                              neural_network.predict(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(images_test)))
# Wizualizacja wyników
print("Confusion_matrix:")
print(conf_matrix_neural_network)
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix_neural_network)

# Wyświetlenie wyniku trafności modelu
acc = accuracy_score(y_test, neural_network.predict(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(images_test)))
print("Neural network model accuracy is {0:0.2f}".format(acc))

from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier

# Import danych
from keras.datasets import fashion_mnist

# Metryki poprawności
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Regresja logistyczna
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Seaborn is a library for making statistical graphics in Python
import seaborn as sns

# Podział na trenujące i testujące
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = fashion_mnist.load_data()

# Krok 1 - utworzenie zbioru trenującego
images_train =  []
for image_train in x_train:
    images_train.append(image_train.flatten())

# Krok 2 - utworzenie zbioru testującego
images_test = []
for image_test in x_test:
    images_test.append(image_test.flatten())

# Krok 3 - utworzenie tablic
images_train = np.array(images_train)
images_test = np.array(images_test)

# Utworzenie sieci neuronowej
siec = MLPClassifier(hidden_layer_sizes=(250,300,100),activation ='logistic', solver="sgd", random_state=1)

# Standaryzacja i nauka modelu
siec.fit(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(images_train), y_train)

# Utworzenie macierzy konfuzji
conf_matrix_neural_network = confusion_matrix(y_test, \
                                              siec.predict(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(images_test)))
# Wizualizacja wyników
print("Confusion_matrix:")
print(conf_matrix_neural_network)
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix_neural_network)

# Wyświetlenie wyniku trafności modelu
acc = accuracy_score(y_test, siec.predict(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(images_test)))
print("Neural network model accuracy is {0:0.2f}".format(acc))

# 2. Train Feed-Forward neural network to recognize hand written digits 
#    using Mnist dataset. Visualize learning process and weights connected to the first layer.
In [13]:
import keras
from keras.datasets import mnist
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
from sklearn import preprocessing

# Metryki poprawności
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

#load mnist dataset
(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test) = mnist.load_data()

print("Datasets size")
print("Train data:", X_train.shape)
print("Test data:", X_test.shape)

print("Samples from training data:")
for i in range(0,10):
    plt.subplot(1,10,i+1)
    plt.imshow(X_train[i], cmap=plt.get_cmap("gray"))
    plt.title(y_train[i]);
    plt.axis('off');
    
# Krok 1 - utworzenie zbioru trenującego
images_train =  []
for image_train in X_train:
    images_train.append(image_train.flatten())

# Krok 2 - utworzenie zbioru testującego
images_test = []
for image_test in X_test:
    images_test.append(image_test.flatten())

# Krok 3 - utworzenie tablic
images_train = np.array(images_train)
images_test = np.array(images_test)

# Utworzenie sieci neuronowej
siec = MLPClassifier(hidden_layer_sizes=(250,300,100),activation ='relu', random_state=1)

# Standaryzacja i nauka modelu
siec.fit(preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(images_train), y_train)

Datasets size
Train data: (60000, 28, 28)
Test data: (10000, 28, 28)
